Headlines.Headline: Archstone Sale Means Lost IPO Fees for Citi, JPM

PARAGRAPH.#text: Archstone’s about-face from initial public offering to sale isn’t happy news for banks on track to lead the offering.Citigroup Inc. and J.P. Morgan Chase & Co. were in line to lead Archstone’s IPO. They would have been the largest recipients in a fee pool in the neighborhood of $100 million, based on the size of Archstone’s planned offering.The offering, expected to raise $3.5 billion, was on track to be the largest offering ever by a real-estate investment trust, according to Dealogic, and the third-largest U.S.-listed IPO of any kind this year.Spokespeople for Citi and J.P. Morgan declined to comment.Now, Archstone’s IPO bankers will have to contend for other roles. Already, some key jobs have been nabbed by others. Equity sales by Avalon Bay and Equity Residential to pay for the cash component of the deal are being led by Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and Morgan Stanley, respectively, according to filings with regulators.

Headlines.Headline: AvalonBay Communities Third-Quarter Net Surges on Rental Revenue

PARAGRAPH.#text: AvalonBay Communities Inc.'s AVB third-quarter income nearly doubled as the multifamily housing real-estate investment trust continued to see its rental revenue grow. The REIT revised its full-year earnings outlook, now seeing per-share earnings of $4.47 to $4.52, down from $5.11 to $5.25 a share. At the same time, it raised its full-year view for funds from operations--a key profitability measure in the real estate sector--seeing $5.45 to $5.50 a share. The company had previously targeted FFO of $5.39 to $5.53 a share.

PARAGRAPH.#text: ROCKVILLE CENTRE, N.Y.--Roxanne George lives in an apartment community boasting everything from a sparkling swimming pool to a state-of-the-art exercise facility. But an even bigger selling point for Ms. George was the dog walk snaking around much of this neighborhood recently developed by AvalonBay Communities Inc. AVB outside of New York City. "This is probably the only amenity that I use multiple times a day," Ms. George said recently as she walked Chloe, her Yorkshire terrier. Rental-apartment complexes throughout the country are replacing "No Pets" signs with dog parks and washing stations as they look for new ways to attract and retain tenants.

Headlines.Headline: EARNINGS PREVIEW: U.S. Multifamily REITs Still See High Occupancy, Rents

PARAGRAPH.#text: TAKING THE PULSE: Some of the same trends that have impeded U.S. homeownership since the recession--including a shaky recovery and skepticism about the market--have fed demand for rental housing. Real-estate investment trusts with a focus on multifamily housing have been the primary beneficiaries, recording high occupancy rates and high rents. This trend looks likely to continue in the near term and has driven a drumbeat of recent housing-property acquisitions. SNL Financial noted that New York and California have attracted the most investment, as UDR Inc. (UDR), Equity Residential (EQR) and others seek to capitalize on the markets that feature the highest rents.

PARAGRAPH.#text: AvalonBay Communities Inc. AVB second-quarter earnings fell 15%, but a key profitability gauge for the real-estate investment trust rose more than targeted on higher rents. Shares in the upscale-apartment owner and builder were down 2.1% at $131.60 after hours on a weak outlook for the current quarter. Last week, the stock hit its highest level since early 2007, before the recession and housing-market crash. Headlines.Author: Joan E. Solsman
Headlines.Headline: AvalonBay Boosts Outlook On Improving Portfolio Trends

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES AvalonBay Communities Inc. AVB raised its profitability projections for the current quarter and the full year Thursday because portfolio trends are better than it expected. The real-estate investment trust, which builds and owns upscale apartments, cited job growth among younger people, a continued decline in home ownership and a record low level of new residential supply as the drivers. Job creation in the first quarter was concentrated in the 20- to 34-year-old age bracket, which is more likely than other groups to rent, the company said.

Futures for the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 26 points to 11098 while those for the S&P 500 index advanced 3.4 points to 1182.10. Nasdaq 100 futures gained 6.25 points to 2130. Wall Street finished on a mostly weaker note on Wednesday, as the market began to fret over the scope and potential for another round of quantitative easing by the Federal Reserve, which holds a key meeting next week.

Headlines.Headline: Avalon Bay 3Q FFO Falls But Not As Far As Downbeat View

PARAGRAPH.#text: AvalonBay Communities Inc.'s AVB third-quarter earnings slumped by 59% as a key measure of the real-estate investment trust's profitability just beat its downbeat guidance. As such, the upscale-apartment owner and builder said 2010 funds from operations, a key profitability metric among REITs, could top the high end of prior estimates as it forecast 98 cents to $1.02 a share for the fourth quarter. Analysts' average estimate was $1, according to Thomson Reuters. Economic occupancy, the level of total possible revenue remaining after stripping out vacancy loss, fell 0.2% in the third quarter from a year ago as average rental rates rose 0.4%.

on Tuesday offered to repurchase up to $300 million of four series of its medium-term notes coming due as soon as next December at a premium. At the same time, the real-estate investment trust - which specializes in high-end apartments - announced plans to sell $500 million in notes, equally split between 8-year and 11-year varieties. Proceeds will go to the tender offer and to repay other debt, similar to what a host of other companies have done through similar capital-raising efforts.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: AvalonBay Plans $300M Note Buyback, $500M Note Sale

Headlines.Author: Danielle Le
Headlines.Headline: US EQUITIES WEEK AHEAD: Dow 14000 Seems Like A World Away

PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Dow 14,000 was barely a week ago, and seemingly a world away. A major underpinning of the recent bull market - the merger-and-acquisition craze, is fraying. Next week, more than ever, market watchers will train attention on financing for outstanding leveraged-buyout deals. Should more cracks such as the jammed bond-offerings for the Chrysler Group and Alliance Boots emerge, the stock market is in jeopardy of further losses. Market participants will see if stock bulls are resting, or have surrendered the field to the bears.

Headlines.Headline: New Year Offers Few Bright Spots

REIT
Interest:
 After a painful year in which stocks of
real-estate investment trusts lost 25% of their value, analysts say there
isn't anything to look forward to in 1999. Few see a big recovery in the
near future.
